The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Nation | Nation Briefs
                                                                                    Saturday , November 14 , 2009                                                                                                                                                                                              NATION BRIEFS
                                      
	 New Delhi, Nov. 13 (PTI): Foreign airlines will be allowed to increase their capacity by up to 10 per cent during peak tourist seasons, the directorate-general of civil aviation has said.           
	According to fresh guidelines issued by the DGCA, national carrier Air India does not need to issue a no-objection certificate to clear the extra flights which fall under bilateral entitlements. Foreign airlines are required to deploy larger aircraft or operate additional flights. These are subject to bilateral air traffic agreements between India and other countries.           
	Earlier, the R.N. Kaw Committee, set up to strengthen the DGCA, had recommended that the practice of obtaining the NOC from the national carrier should be done away with.                   
	 New Delhi (PTI): Uttar Pradesh recorded the highest number of cases last year under the Prevention of Domestic Violence Act, closely followed by Delhi and Kerala. A study was conducted by the National Commission for Women to evaluate the implementation of the act.                  
	 New Delhi (PTI): The National Commission for Women has said its staff had made no errors while recording the statement of Komal Singh, the Air India airhostess whose allegations of molestation by pilots on duty were dismissed by the airlines. Komal had complained that the typist who wrote down her statement had made some mistakes.                  
	 Srinagar (PTI): An army jawan killed himself in Jammu and Kashmirs Kupwara district on Friday. Sepoy Sandeep Singh shot himself with his service rifle inside a forward post at Kachal, 165km from Srinagar. The reason for the suicide has not been determined.                  
	 Erode (PTI): More than 100 students fell ill after eating the free noon meal in a government school in Erode district of Tamil Nadu. A dead lizard was allegedly found in the food, prompting protests by parents. Several students were found vomiting.                                                                                                                                                               
